  "prompt": "How does the law define illegal money laundering activities?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally-obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex financial transactions or legitimate businesses. Specific legal definitions can vary between jurisdictions, but typically involve three key stages:\n\n1. Placement: Introducing illegal funds into the financial system\n2. Layering: Concealing the source of the money through complex transactions\n3. Integration: Withdrawing the now \"cleaned\" money into legitimate accounts\n\nSpecific activities often considered money laundering include:\n- Structuring cash deposits to avoid reporting requirements\n- Using shell companies to hide fund origins\n- Transferring money through multiple accounts\n- Mixing illegal funds with legitimate business income\n\nThe specific legal definitions and penalties vary by country, with most developed nations having comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) laws.\n\nWould you like me to provide more details about money laundering from a legal perspective?",
